RedDoorz.InfoLeak: In September 2020, booking platform RedDoorz suffered a data breach. Data from 5.8 million user accounts were exposed. The hacked data included names, email addresses, phone numbers, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of bcrypt hashes.

Tokopedia.InfoLeak: In April 2020, Indonesia's largest online store was hacked. The hacker forum posted 90 million lines of data, including emails, names, gender, dates of birth and passwords in the form of SHA2-384 hashes.

Wahana Express.InfoLeak: Wahana is a large Indonesian transport company. At the beginning of 2022, about 17 million records of deliveries by this service were publicly available. The data contains names, addresses, data about parcels and their costs, as well as one or two phone numbers.

BukalaPak.InfoLeak: In March 2019, Indonesian e-commerce website Bukalapak discovered a data breach of the organization's backups dating back to October 2017. The incident exposed approximately 13 million unique email addresses, as well as IP addresses, names and passwords in bcrypt and SHA hashes. 512 with salt.

Cutout.pro.InfoLeak: Cutout is a website for photo editing using artificial intelligence. In February 2024, the site suffered a hack that resulted in the publication of data on 22 million users. The information includes names, emails, IP addresses and passwords in the form of salted MD5 hashes.

Bureau van Dijk.InfoLeak: Around July 2021, business information publisher specializing in “private company data,” Bureau van Dijk, suffered a data breach. The violation included full names, email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses, dates of birth, job titles, European VAT numbers, tax numbers, patent numbers, patents. names, company names and other data. A total of 484 million rows of data.

Instagram Parsing.InfoLeak: In 2022, the Instagram user base, collected through parsing, began to spread in Telegram channels. The date of data collection is unknown, but the database contains 17 million records, including names, emails, phone numbers, nicknames and addresses.

MyPertamina.InfoLeak: In November 2022, Indonesian oil and gas company Pertamina suffered a data breach on its MyPertamina service. The incident revealed 44 million records with 6 million unique email addresses, as well as names, dates of birth, gender, physical addresses and purchases.

Dukcapil.InfoLeak: In 2023, it became known about a data leak from Dukcapil, a government service for document management in Indonesia. According to experts, more than 337 million records were stolen, but only 24 million of them were publicly available. The data contains telephone numbers, names, dates of birth, addresses and NIK numbers, which are used in the ID card.

IndonesiaCarOwner.InfoLeak: In 2021, a file containing information about car owners in Indonesia appeared online. The data contains 35 million records, including names and addresses of owners, as well as vehicle data - make, model, color, year of manufacture, VIN, as well as BPKB and NIK numbers, which are used in documents as identification information.
